4. DIMENSIONLESS COUPLING AND PHASE TRANSITION
======================================================================
  p=  3: g=1.103, lambda_P=1.000, lambda_I=0.955, ratio=0.955, winner=Paley
  p=  7: g=1.684, lambda_P=1.414, lambda_I=2.228, ratio=1.576, winner=Paley
  p= 11: g=2.111, lambda_P=1.732, lambda_I=3.501, ratio=2.022, winner=Paley
  p= 13: g=2.295, lambda_P=1.871, lambda_I=4.138, ratio=2.212, winner=Paley
  p= 19: g=2.775, lambda_P=2.236, lambda_I=6.048, ratio=2.705, winner=Interval
  p= 23: g=3.053, lambda_P=2.449, lambda_I=7.321, ratio=2.989, winner=Interval
  p= 31: g=3.545, lambda_P=2.828, lambda_I=9.868, ratio=3.489, winner=Interval
  p= 43: g=4.175, lambda_P=3.317, lambda_I=13.687, ratio=4.127, winner=Interval
  p= 47: g=4.364, lambda_P=3.464, lambda_I=14.961, ratio=4.319, winner=Interval

INTERPRETATION:
  g = 2*sqrt(p)/pi is the dimensionless coupling.
  At g < g_c (small p): 2-body Ising dominates → Paley ground state
  At g > g_c (large p): many-body dominance → Interval ground state

  g(p=11) = 2.11, g(p=13) = 2.29, g(p=19) = 2.77

  The crossover happens between p=13 and p=19.
  Critical coupling g_c ≈ 2.3-2.5.

======================================================================
5. HESSIAN EIGENVALUE DECOMPOSITION AT p=19
======================================================================
Hessian eigenvalues at Paley (p=19):
  lambda_0 = -1.4327e+10
  lambda_1 = -1.4327e+10
  lambda_2 = -1.2580e+10
  lambda_3 = -1.2580e+10
  lambda_4 = -1.1489e+10
  lambda_5 = -1.1489e+10
  lambda_6 = -8.9358e+09
  lambda_7 = -8.9358e+09
  lambda_8 = 1.5040e+10

Multiplicity pattern: [2, 2, 2, 2, 1]
Expected from QR irreps of C_m (m=9):
  m=9 → (m-1)/2 = 4 conjugate pairs + 1 trivial → 4 pairs + 1 = 5 eigenvalues
  Multiplicities: [2,2,2,2,1] ✓

The POSITIVE eigenvalue (1.5040e+10) is the trivial QR irrep direction.
This is the direction where ALL chords are flipped coherently.
Since H(σ) = H(-σ), this isn't the all-flip — it's the PALEY direction itself.

ISING INTERPRETATION:
  The 2-body Ising term makes Paley a ground state (THM-137).
  The 4-body term adds curvature. At p=19:

  In 4 directions (8 eigenvalues, paired): curvature is NEGATIVE
    → Paley IS a local max in these directions
    → These are the "transverse" fluctuations

  In 1 direction (1 eigenvalue): curvature is POSITIVE
    → Paley is a saddle point in this direction!
    → This is the "longitudinal" mode = the Paley direction
    → Moving AWAY from Paley alignment increases H
    → This is the 4-body term overwhelming the 2-body term

  At p=7,11: ALL Hessian eigenvalues would be negative
    → Paley is a true maximum (verified: it IS the global max)

  At p=19: ONE positive eigenvalue
    → The phase transition has occurred
    → The positive direction points toward Interval

======================================================================
6. PALEY vs INTERVAL: ORIENTATION GEOMETRY
======================================================================
Paley σ_P = [ 1 -1 -1  1  1  1  1 -1  1]
Interval σ_I = [1 1 1 1 1 1 1 1 1]

QR alignment A(σ) = Σ chi(k) σ_k:
  A(Paley) = 9 = m (maximal)
  A(Interval) = 3
  A(Interval)/m = 0.3333

Hamming distance d(P,I) = 3 (out of 9)
Fractional distance = 0.3333
Inner product <σ_P, σ_I>/m = 0.3333

Chords where P ≠ I: [2, 3, 8]
  chord 2: chi(2) = -1, so 2 is NQR
  chord 3: chi(3) = -1, so 3 is NQR
  chord 8: chi(8) = -1, so 8 is NQR

The NQR elements in {1,...,m}: [2, 3, 8]
Interval differs from Paley at EXACTLY the NQR chord types!
Interval flips all NQR chords to CW — ignoring the quadratic residue structure.

